{
  "doc_id": "1011",
  "text": "[5] Biomass burning, natural emissions, and use of fossil fuels are the main sources of NMHC and methyl chloride in the atmosphere. The influence of biomass burning and use of fossil fuels can be estimated in Antarctica by use of methyl chloride and ethane, because the relatively long atmospheric lifetimes (t) of methyl chloride (t = 1.5 years) [CITATION_1] and ethane (t = 92 days) [CITATION_2] permits long-range transport from anthropogenic sources to remote regions. Oceans contribute approximately 10% to the atmospheric NMHC concentrations [CITATION_3] and significantly to the methyl chloride concentration [CITATION_4] . This makes the oceans an important source of these gases, and for Antarctica the only local source. Background levels for propane and acetylene are therefore relatively undisturbed by local events in Antarctica.",
